pull_request.title: Change trace in ebpf_pinning_table_find
pull_request.body:
## Description

**Problem:**
 ebpf_pinning_table_find() returns EBPF_RETURN_RESULT(retval), which prints success or failure trace upon return.

In _ebpf_native_reuse_map(), ebpf_pinning_table_find() was printing a trace with an error.
It is not an error if the Key is not found in the pinning table, as there will be no entry for the newly created map.

**Solution:**
 - Removed the EBPF_RETURN_RESULT and added to return the retval, without trace.
 - The ebpf_core_get_pinned_object() caller will print the success trace.
 - The callers will print the error trace:
   1.  _ebpf_native_reuse_map()
   2. _ebpf_core_protocol_get_pinned_object()

## Testing

_Do any existing tests cover this change? Are new tests needed? No

pull_request.title: Add support for in-mem etl traces for CI/CD jobs
pull_request.body:
## Description

This PR adds support for generation of 'in-memory' ETL trace for CI/CD jobs.  This is required for jobs (km stress tests, for now) that can potentially generate .etl files of unbounded size.

The in-memory .etl traces are restricted to memory buffers of the specified size which are then treated as a circular buffer.

## Testing
CI/CD runs.

_Do any existing tests cover this change? Are new tests needed?_
No tests needed (This is a CI/CD workflow enhancement).

## Documentation
No doc changes.

## Installation
No installer impact.

Fixes #2932

issue.title: Delete c:\eBPF folder on self-hosted runner VMs in post-cleanup, and uninstall Duonic.

labels.name: blocked
labels.description: Blocked on another issue that must be done first

issue.body:
### Describe the bug

During regular operation leaving the test artifacts on the VM is fine - when a new job is scheduled the VMs are restored to the `baseline` checkpoint.
However, when I worked on the VMs and updated the checkpoint, it included the c:\ebpf folder left over from a previous run, also Duonic services were running.
Because of this, when a new job is scheduled on the 'restored' VM, during artifact copying the existing `dswdevice.exe` cannot be unlinked and replaced with the Duonic collateral and the job fails.

Solution - uninstall duonic and delete c:\ebpf directory in the post-cleanup step. That way, when maintenance is done on the VMs, the perosn won't need to remember to do it before updating the `baseline` checkpoint, and then spend time fixing it later.

pull_request.title: Restore VM after driver job finishes.
pull_request.body:
## Description

Fixes #2913 

Restore VM checkpoint after `driver `job finishes.
If Duonic devices are accidentally persisted in the checkpoint during runner maintenance,
it causes subsequent test runs to fail.

This is a workaround for us not being able to cleanly uninstall Duonic currently.

In cases where we want to manually grab a dump if it failed to upload, this checkpoint restore comes after the dump was copied to the runner host. So this doesn't reduce the amount of time we'd have to do that before another job is scheduled on a given runner.
